******
[2]
Date: 11 March 2008
Source: NewsMail [edited]
<http://www.news-mail.com.au/storydisplay.cfm?storyid=3766275>


Call made for calm on smut issue
--------------------------------
Fears about smut resistant sugarcane being found infected with the disease
in north Queensland appears not to have turned Bundaberg growers off the
Q200 variety. Bundaberg Canegrowers chairman Allan Dingle said he was
unconcerned by the smut discovery in the Q200 variety in Ingham. "All
varieties have some susceptibility, but on a scale of one to 9, one being
the best, Q200 is a one, so it will not endanger productivity," Mr Dingle
said. He said 99 per cent of the canegrowers in Bundaberg were growing
resistant varieties.

Isis Canegrowers chairman Joe Russo said removing susceptible varieties was
still the best way to battle the cane disease. "I don't think we will ever
get rid of smut outright, it's about managing it properly with resistant
varieties," Mr Russo said. "It's nothing to get overwhelmed about, but it
does stress the importance of getting rid of susceptible varieties. The
disease devastates the profitability of sugarcane crops by significantly
reducing their productivity and yield. Resistant varieties like Q200 are
considered by experts to be less likely to be affected, and retain better
productivity if they are."

[byline: Kallee Buchanan]

