******
[4]
Date: 27 February 2008
Source: Channel Nine News Money [edited]
<http://money.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=384881>


Smut disease spreads in Australia sugar industry
------------------------------------------------
Sugarcane smut disease, which affects productivity, had spread to the
Innisfail district in north east Queensland state, the Bureau of Sugar
Experiment Stations [BSES] said on Wednesday [27 Feb 2008].

This follows the 1st discovery of the fungal disease in the Australian
sugarcane crop early last year [2007] in the Bundaberg region, about 280
kilometres (174 miles) north of the city of Brisbane. It later spread
northwards to Mackay and Townsville, around 200 kilometres south of Innisfail.

"Being a windborne fungal disease, there was a high chance it would spread
to the Innisfail area, but it is still unfortunate that such an incursion
has now occurred," BSES chief executive officer Eoin Wallis said on
Wednesday. The disease had recently intensified in the Herbert district,
about 150 km south of Innisfail, he said. However, the Tully district
between the Herbert and Innisfail districts remained free of smut, he said.

Smut is a highly contagious fungal disease which stunts plants and impedes
re-growth. It is believed to have been carried into Queensland by spores
borne through the upper atmosphere from the west, probably from Indonesia.
BSES is a research organisation servicing Australia's sugar cane industry.
The Australian sugar industry stretches 2000 kilometres along the
Queensland coastline, and is the world's 3rd-largest exporter.

[byline: Michael Byrnes, Reuters]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Sugarcane smut is caused by the fungus _Sporisorium scitamineum_. It is
highly contagious and can be spread by wind or carried on clothing and
machinery. Symptoms are a black whip-like structure emerging from the
central core of meristematic tissues. The whip contains spores covered with
a thin membrane which ruptures easily to release the spores. Smut spores
survive for long periods in soil or plant debris. Disease management may
include removal of inoculum, burning of infected cane fields, fungicides
and use of clean planting material. However, smut control is best achieved
by using resistant cane cultivars available for different regions.

Australia was the last cane growing country worldwide considered to be free
of smut until the disease was found in 1998 in Western Australia, a minor
cane growing area, and in June 2006 in Queensland. In less than 2 years it
has spread to all the main sugar growing regions of Queensland, despite
efforts to contain the disease. Existing cane varieties are being screened
for smut resistance, management and monitoring programmes have been
implemented, and development of high-yielding resistant cultivars
continues. A programme of replacing susceptible with smut resistant
varieties is in progress. Replacement is mandatory when replanting, but
ratoon crops of already planted susceptible varieties may still be
harvested. It will, therefore, take several years before a complete
transition to resistant varieties will be achieved.

The term 'resistant' is often used loosely for plant varieties to include
complete or partial resistance or tolerance to a pathogen. This may lead to
confusion, as it has in the news stories above. 'Resistance' describes a
situation when a plant cannot be infected by a pathogen, while 'tolerance'
will allow the host to survive despite the infection. The cane varieties
referred to above appear to have varying degrees of tolerance, since smut
is reported to still develop on them, but at a lower level and without
affecting yield.

